{{Main|Maryland Terrapins football under Jim Tatum (1947â1955)}} {{NCAATeamFootballSeason |Year=1950 |Team=Maryland Terrapins |Image= |Conference=Southern Conference |Division= |ShortConference=SoCon |Record= 7â2â1 |ConfRecord= 4â1â1 |CoachRank= |APRank= |HeadCoach=[[Jim Tatum]] |OffCoach= |DefCoach= |Captain= [[Ray Krouse]] and Jake Rowden |OScheme=[[Split-T]] |DScheme= |StadiumArena=[[Byrd Stadium]] |Champion= |BowlTourney= |BowlTourneyResult= }} The '''1950 Maryland Terrapins football team''' represented the [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] in [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[college football]] in its [[1950 college football season|30th season]] as a member of the [[Southern Conference]].
Maryland was led by fourth-year head coach [[Jim Tatum]], who ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine called "the most successful major college coach in the game" [[Maryland Terrapins football under Jim Tatum (1947â1955)|during his nine-year tenure]] at [[College Park, Maryland|College Park]].<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,825833,00.html The Coach], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', August 3, 1959.</ref> To date, Tatum remains the winningest Maryland football coach of the modern era, with a [[winning percentage]] of 0.819.<ref>[http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/acc/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/07fbguide051056.pdf Records] (PDF), 2007 Maryland Terrapins Football Media Guide, University of Maryland, p. 55, retrieved 14 January 2009. [http://www.webcitation.org/5gbBdoqwJ Archived] 2009-05-07.</ref> The team was led on the field by sophomore [[quarterback]] and future [[Heisman Trophy]] runner-up [[Jack Scarbath]] who made his first career start in the season-opener.<ref name="p280"/>
The highlight of the season was Maryland's upset victory over second-ranked [[Michigan State Spartans football|Michigan State]], 34â7, in what was that team's only loss of the season. Two weeks later, however, the Terrapins' bowl game hopes were ended with a [[Homecoming]] defeat at the hands of [[North Carolina State Wolfpack football|North Carolina State]].
